Size of Data Types

In C, each data type has a unique set of operations that can be done on it and varied memory requirements. 
The type of data that the variable can store, such as character, integer, float etc.

Examples of Calculating the Size of Data type

Classification of Data Types in C:

Types	Illustration
Primitive Data Type	Primitive data types are used as the most fundamental data types in programming languages. 
Examples of primitive data types are byte, character, sort, int, boolean, long, float and double.
User Defined Data Type	A user-defined data type is a data type that can be derived from an existing data type.
Examples of user-defined data types are an array, pointer, structure and union.
Void Data Type	A void data type is a data type that doesn’t have any value or operator, and it doesn’t give any response to its caller. 
A void data type comes from a primitive data type.
Derived Data Type	A derived data type is a data type that is derived from built-in or primitive data types.
